H0.text: A single cell becomes many cells is the best description of the development of a human embryo.

H1.text: Each cell has a different function is the statement that best describes the development of a human embryo.

H2.text: Many cells combine to form one cell best describes the development of a human embryo.

H3.text: All the cells have the same function is the statement that best describes the development of a human embryo.

A4.text: the development of the human body entails growth from a one-celled zygote to an adult human being

A5.text: cell division and cellular differentiation of the embryo that occurs during the early stages of development

A6.text: The zygote undergoes many cell divisions that produce cells known as blastomeres.

A7.text: During organogenesis, molecular and cellular interactions prompt certain populations of cells from the different germ layers to differentiate into organ-specific cell types.

A8.text: After four divisions, the conceptus consists of 16 blastomeres, and it is known as the morula.

A9.text: Through the processes of compaction, cell division, and blastulation, the conceptus takes the form of the blastocyst by the fifth day of development.
